g.aria-label: (a) Two Petri dishes A and B, contain a layer of sand of equal depth. Water is added to dish A such that a layer of width 'd' is formed over the sand and a glass slab of width 'd' is placed on the sand in dish B. It is observed that the sand in the dish A appears darker than the sand in dish B. Provide an explanation for this observation and compare these two cases with the case when just sand is present in the Petri dish.
(b) Another set-up is made with Petri dishes C and D as shown in figure 1.
The water layer and the glass slab have equal width in both. Cand D. In which case will the sand appear darker"? Explain.

1. Incident light on the sand undergoes diffused reflection. Any light incident at the water-air interface at angles > the critical angle undergoes TIR and gets absorbed or reflected by the sand. The output intensity is less than the input intensity due to TIR, hence the sand appears darker. The glass slab is a perfect cuboid and no TIR takes place (consider the limiting case when light is incident on the glass slab at 90 deg; this light is emitted at 90deg .. no TIR), hence the sand doesnt appear dark. Absorption is considered negligible. On comparing the cases with the case with only sand, the order is sand > b> a: brightness. 2. In set-up D, the glass-water layer effectively as a solid slab of differential optical index and no TIR occurs. Hence, the sand doesnt appear dark. In set-up C, theres no TIR at the water-glass interface. The maximum angle of incidence at the glass-air interface(9; max) is Sin-1(8/9) and the critical angle for the glass-air interface is Sin-1(6/9). The light incident at angles between ;,max and Sin-1(6/9) undergoes TIR and is absorbed or reflected.
